WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.260
And a lot of my talk has already been discussed before, so this should be pretty quick.

00:00:06.260 --> 00:00:11.780
So, you know, as it's just been discussed, this degrader basically ubiquitinates the

00:00:11.780 --> 00:00:16.740
BTK enzyme, leading to degradation through the proteasome.

00:00:17.500 --> 00:00:19.480
And this is done through the E3 ligase.

00:00:20.620 --> 00:00:25.420
The, you know, with this approach, you could bypass some of the mutations that are typically

00:00:25.420 --> 00:00:34.560
seen with covalent or non-covalent BTK inhibitors, such as C481 or the other mutations, including

00:00:34.560 --> 00:00:36.320
474, for example.

00:00:37.480 --> 00:00:39.600
This is just some preclinical data.

00:00:40.020 --> 00:00:46.920
It showed that, you know, in xenograft models, you get a deep and durable tumor suppression

00:00:46.920 --> 00:00:53.640
in wild type, as well as C481 BTK mutated tumors.

00:00:53.880 --> 00:00:55.040
This has already been...

00:00:55.420 --> 00:00:56.380
Again, discussed.

00:00:56.600 --> 00:00:58.100
This is the phase one data.

00:01:00.160 --> 00:01:01.600
You know, and when we have...

00:01:01.600 --> 00:01:05.280
I have here on the right side, just the summary of the CLL data.

00:01:05.280 --> 00:01:06.560
You could see it's very...

00:01:06.560 --> 00:01:08.820
You know, these are patients who are very heavily pre-treated.

00:01:09.120 --> 00:01:13.680
A lot of them have BTK mutations in 39% of patients.

00:01:14.140 --> 00:01:19.760
They've all been exposed to covalent BTK inhibitors, some to non-covalent BTK inhibitors,

00:01:19.920 --> 00:01:20.740
BCL2 inhibitors.

00:01:20.800 --> 00:01:23.660
So, again, a very heavily pre-treated group of patients.

00:01:24.240 --> 00:01:24.880
And...

00:01:24.880 --> 00:01:27.880
Responses are, you know, very promising.

00:01:28.060 --> 00:01:32.240
So, 85% overall response in this CLL group.

00:01:32.520 --> 00:01:36.500
And if you look at the subgroup analysis, you know, there's definitely activity.

00:01:36.700 --> 00:01:40.260
For example, like patients who have seen a covalent as well as a BTK inhibitor,

00:01:40.300 --> 00:01:43.180
as well as a BCL2 inhibitor, overall response, 93%.

00:01:43.180 --> 00:01:47.240
Patients with the BTK mutations, we're seeing an overall response of 77%.

00:01:47.820 --> 00:01:50.740
So, again, the agent is definitely very active.

00:01:51.280 --> 00:01:54.240
And if you look at the PFS on the right-hand side here,

00:01:54.260 --> 00:01:59.380
you could definitely see that those patients with or without BTK mutations

00:01:59.380 --> 00:02:02.140
had similar PFS.

00:02:04.020 --> 00:02:08.020
The safety profile, obviously, again, these are, you know,

00:02:08.060 --> 00:02:10.420
this is still very early in development.

00:02:11.260 --> 00:02:14.980
It seems that it has, you know, similar safety profile

00:02:14.980 --> 00:02:17.220
to what we typically would see with a BTK degrader.

00:02:17.340 --> 00:02:22.340
Although, one thing that we want to keep an eye on is the incidence of neutropenia.

00:02:22.340 --> 00:02:24.240
We're seeing a grade 3 or higher.

00:02:24.260 --> 00:02:26.040
Neutropenia of 25%.

00:02:26.040 --> 00:02:28.960
But, again, you know, this is a very heavily pre-treated group of patients,

00:02:29.040 --> 00:02:31.800
and it's not uncommon initially to see, you know,

00:02:31.840 --> 00:02:34.580
these patients have issues with bone marrow reserve.

00:02:35.540 --> 00:02:39.020
And I think, you know, more data will be needed in subsequent studies.

00:02:39.500 --> 00:02:42.880
Also, the infection complications is something to keep an eye on.

00:02:42.980 --> 00:02:46.180
There was 12% grade 3 or higher pneumonias here.

00:02:46.280 --> 00:02:50.720
So, again, you know, something to keep in mind as the data evolves.

00:02:50.720 --> 00:02:54.140
So, it makes a lot of sense to combine.

00:02:54.140 --> 00:02:57.060
This agent now with, you know, other modalities.

00:02:57.660 --> 00:03:03.420
I think the, you know, one of the interesting concepts would be to combine it

00:03:03.420 --> 00:03:06.580
with a BCL2 inhibitor like Sonratoclax, for example,

00:03:07.180 --> 00:03:11.720
where basically, you know, you get a deep and strong inhibition of the BTK pathway.

00:03:12.620 --> 00:03:17.340
And this would, you know, basically work on the upstream survival signaling.

00:03:17.820 --> 00:03:21.800
And at the same time, you know, you would work with a BCL2 inhibitor

00:03:21.800 --> 00:03:23.800
to control the, you know, the apoptosis.

00:03:24.020 --> 00:03:29.180
And this would, you know, potentially lead to synergy and reduces the, you know,

00:03:29.220 --> 00:03:33.520
hopefully at least theoretically reduce the incidence of, you know, a resistance mechanism.

00:03:34.140 --> 00:03:40.540
So, the study that I was, you know, that we're currently enrolling on is the 104 study.

00:03:40.660 --> 00:03:46.000
Now, this is the combination study combining the BTK degrader with a number of other agents.

00:03:46.600 --> 00:03:50.660
So, Sonratoclax, there's an arm with Xanabrutinib, there's an arm with Nosonatuzumab,

00:03:53.900 --> 00:03:58.140
you know, it's a big, you know, basically basket trial.

00:03:59.020 --> 00:04:03.660
I wanted to, you know, to highlight one of these patients that I saw in clinic

00:04:03.660 --> 00:04:07.320
and one of the very first, you know, few patients that we enrolled on the study.

00:04:07.980 --> 00:04:10.140
So, basically, this is a 76-year-old lady.

00:04:10.600 --> 00:04:13.140
She came in with, you know, CLL.

00:04:13.220 --> 00:04:14.580
She was diagnosed in 2009.

00:04:15.440 --> 00:04:17.760
She had already pretty much seen everything.

00:04:17.760 --> 00:04:23.400
I mean, you know, she's seen back in the day, she's had FCR, BR, Ibrutinib, Venetoclax,

00:04:23.780 --> 00:04:26.380
Acalabrutinib, Duvalisib, Pertrabrutinib.

00:04:26.960 --> 00:04:33.140
And, you know, she was referred to us to discuss, you know, either a Bispecific or CAR TCL therapy.

00:04:34.040 --> 00:04:38.100
And, you know, on the first day of her visit, you know, she was, oh, you know, I've had this, you know,

00:04:38.140 --> 00:04:41.800
pretty bad pain in my hip and I can't walk and I'm using a walker for the last two weeks.

00:04:41.900 --> 00:04:42.320
It's like, hmm.

00:04:43.060 --> 00:04:49.980
So, we imaged it and basically, you know, she had a lot of tumor infiltration in her bones with a pathological fracture.

00:04:49.980 --> 00:04:52.220
I told her, listen, I mean, this is probably going to be Richter's.

00:04:53.660 --> 00:04:57.460
And, you know, one of the surgeons took her and, you know, she had like fixation and whatnot.

00:04:57.680 --> 00:05:02.640
And they obviously took, you know, that big surgical biopsy was not Richter's.

00:05:02.660 --> 00:05:04.420
It was just the CLL from hell, basically.

00:05:05.540 --> 00:05:08.180
So, we put her on the study.

00:05:09.120 --> 00:05:09.760
One more thing.

00:05:09.820 --> 00:05:14.360
So, if you look at her genomic profile, so she, of course, has a TP53, not surprisingly.

00:05:15.140 --> 00:05:16.160
She's unmutated.

00:05:16.780 --> 00:05:23.540
She has the T474 mutation, which would confer resistance to a covalent as well as non-covalent.

00:05:23.540 --> 00:05:25.280
She has the covalent BDK inhibitors.

00:05:25.280 --> 00:05:30.720
She's refractory dystrophinatic lax, not surprisingly, because she has two BCL2 mutations.

00:05:31.180 --> 00:05:35.340
And you could see here, so when it went, you know, when she started, she was transfusion dependent.

00:05:35.340 --> 00:05:44.660
She was getting blood and platelets and you could see here the curves for, you know, the hemoglobin and the platelets, you know, they gradually improved over the next few weeks.

00:05:45.160 --> 00:05:53.420
You could clearly see, you know, the jump in the white counts, you know, white blood cells, and then it would go down similar to what you would similarly see when you're getting a response

00:05:53.420 --> 00:05:56.100
with a BDK inhibitor in these patients.

00:05:57.140 --> 00:06:03.920
And the study, you know, for, you know, we don't have PET scans on her, but, you know, we had CT imaging.

00:06:04.940 --> 00:06:12.860
And, you know, when she walked in, she had, like, you know, these huge neck lymph nodes and pretty much in two weeks, you know, they pretty much went away.

00:06:13.700 --> 00:06:22.940
And you could see here on the images, so she, you know, you could clearly see, you know, accelerated ethnopathy bilaterally, you could see by, you know, retroperitoneal ethnopathy.

00:06:23.300 --> 00:06:33.980
And this is her most recent scan three months later, after, you know, starting this, you could clearly see a resolution of, you know, the axillary ethnopathy, as well as the retroperitoneal ethnopathy.

00:06:34.300 --> 00:06:46.980
So this is, you know, this is a very active, you know, agent, especially with the potential synergy with other agents like BCL2 inhibition, or, you know, the bispecific data.

00:06:46.980 --> 00:06:53.180
So, you know, something to keep an eye on, of course, we have to, you know, just monitor the, you know, the safety of these approaches.

00:06:53.180 --> 00:07:02.000
Because again, you know, when you're combining things, you could always, you know, you know, run into issues with, you know, infectious complications and whatnot.

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:03.140
So we'll see how that turns out.

00:07:03.620 --> 00:07:05.420
And we're happy to answer any of your questions.

00:07:05.480 --> 00:07:05.840
Thank you.
